<p><a href="/UkuleleWeb">UkuleleWeb</a> stores the markdown of all pages in plain text files, so that you can use normal file system utilities to create backups or historical archives.</p>
<h2>Example: Use <code>git</code></h2>
<p>A simple option is to put your wiki directory under git version control. In a periodic cron job, execute the following git command:</p>
<pre><code class="language-good">git commit -am 'Periodic changes'
</code></pre>
<h2>Example: Use other backup tools</h2>
<p>Any other file system backup tool will work as well to create an archive of your wiki contents.</p>
<h2>Example: Use built-in file system versioning</h2>
<p>Some file systems offer built-in snapshots or file versioning.  This is often the case for Copy-on-Write file systems like ZFS or <a href="https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Btrfs">BtrFS</a>.</p>
